Travel Package Purchase Prediction - Problem Statement¶

Description¶

Background and Context¶

You are a Data Scientist for a tourism company named "Visit with us". The Policy Maker of the company wants to enable and establish a viable business model to expand the customer base.

A viable business model is a central concept that helps you to understand the existing ways of doing the business and how to change the ways for the benefit of the tourism sector.

One of the ways to expand the customer base is to introduce a new offering of packages.

Currently, there are 5 types of packages the company is offering - Basic, Standard, Deluxe, Super Deluxe, King. Looking at the data of the last year, we observed that 18% of the customers purchased the packages.

However, the marketing cost was quite high because customers were contacted at random without looking at the available information.

The company is now planning to launch a new product i.e. Wellness Tourism Package. Wellness Tourism is defined as Travel that allows the traveler to maintain, enhance or kick-start a healthy lifestyle, and support or increase one's sense of well-being.

However, this time company wants to harness the available data of existing and potential customers to make the marketing expenditure more efficient.

You as a Data Scientist at "Visit with us" travel company have to analyze the customers' data and information to provide recommendations to the Policy Maker and Marketing Team and also build a model to predict the potential customer who is going to purchase the newly introduced travel package.

Objective¶

To predict which customer is more likely to purchase the newly introduced travel package.

Data Dictionary¶

Customer details:¶

  • CustomerID: Unique customer ID
  • ProdTaken: Whether the customer has purchased a package or not (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Age: Age of customer
  • TypeofContact: How customer was contacted (Company Invited or Self Inquiry)
  • CityTier: City tier depends on the development of a city, population, facilities, and living standards. The categories are ordered i.e. Tier 1 > Tier 2 > Tier 3
  • Occupation: Occupation of customer
  • Gender: Gender of customer
  • NumberOfPersonVisiting: Total number of persons planning to take the trip with the customer
  • PreferredPropertyStar: Preferred hotel property rating by customer
  • MaritalStatus: Marital status of customer
  • NumberOfTrips: Average number of trips in a year by customer
  • Passport: The customer has a passport or not (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • OwnCar: Whether the customers own a car or not (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • NumberOfChildrenVisiting: Total number of children with age less than 5 planning to take the trip with the customer
  • Designation: Designation of the customer in the current organization
  • MonthlyIncome: Gross monthly income of the customer

Customer interaction data:¶

  • PitchSatisfactionScore: Sales pitch satisfaction score
  • ProductPitched: Product pitched by the salesperson
  • NumberOfFollowups: Total number of follow-ups has been done by the salesperson after the sales pitch
  • DurationOfPitch: Duration of the pitch by a salesperson to the customer

# Function to create both boxplot and histogram that will contain both mean and median values of applicable variables.
def hist_boxplt(feature, figsize=(15, 10), bins=None):
    sns.set(font_scale=2)
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,
        sharex=True,
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="red")
    sns.distplot(feature, kde=True, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins) if bins else sns.distplot(
        feature, kde=True, ax=ax_hist2
    )
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color="g", linestyle="--")
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color="black", linestyle="-")

    


# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.
def perc_on_bar(feature):
    total = len(feature)  # length of the column
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    ax = sns.countplot(feature, palette="bright")
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = "{:.1f}%".format(
            100 * p.get_height() / total
        )  # to show percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05  # defining width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()  # defining the height of the plot

        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size=15)  # to annotate the percantage
    plt.show()  # to show the plot

# Function to plot stacked bar charts for Personal_Loan against other variables
def stacked_plot(x):
    sns.set()
    ## crosstab
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(x, df["ProdTaken"], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=1, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    ## visualising the cross tab
    tab = pd.crosstab(x, df["ProdTaken"], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=1, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(17, 7))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left",
        frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting a customer will purchase a travel package but actually did not .
  2. Predicting a customer will not purchase a travel package but actually did

Which case is more important?¶

  • Both the cases are important as: a) If we predict a customer will purchase a travel package but actually did not purchase, the time and other resources used in marketing travel package to that customer will be a waste, thereby contributing to more marketing expenditure and its less efficiency. b) If we predict a customer will not purchase a travel package but did purchase, the Visit-With-Us's marketing department would have excluded such potential customer from their next marketing campaign.

How to improve marketing expense efficiency i.e need to reduce misclassifications(both False Positives and False Negatives?¶

  • f1_score should be maximized. The greater the f1_score, the higher the chances of identifying both the classes correctly.

Fist, we will create two functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix.

In [73]:
##  Function to calculate different metric scores of the model - Accuracy, Recall, Precision, and F1_score
def model_perf(model,flag=True):
    
    # defining an empty list to store train and test results
    score_list=[] 
    
    #Predicting on train and tests
    pred_train = model.predict(x_train)
    pred_test = model.predict(x_test)
    
    #Accuracy of the model
    train_acc = model.score(x_train,y_train)
    test_acc = model.score(x_test,y_test)
    
    #Recall of the model
    train_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_train,pred_train)
    test_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_test,pred_test)
    
    #Precision of the model
    train_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_train,pred_train)
    test_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_test,pred_test)
    
    #F1 of the model
    train_f1=metrics.f1_score(y_train,pred_train)
    test_f1= metrics.f1_score(y_test,pred_test)
    
    score_list.extend((train_acc,test_acc,train_recall,test_recall,train_precision,test_precision, train_f1, test_f1))
        
    # If the flag is set to True then only the following print statements will be dispayed. The default value is set to True.
    if flag == True: 
        print("Accuracy on training set : ",model.score(x_train,y_train))
        print("Accuracy on test set : ",model.score(x_test,y_test))
        print("Recall on training set : ",metrics.recall_score(y_train,pred_train))
        print("Recall on test set : ",metrics.recall_score(y_test,pred_test))
        print("Precision on training set : ",metrics.precision_score(y_train,pred_train))
        print("Precision on test set : ",metrics.precision_score(y_test,pred_test))
        print('F1_Score on training set:', metrics.f1_score(y_train,pred_train))
        print('F1_Score on test set:',metrics.f1_score(y_test,pred_test))
    
    else:
        return score_list # returning the list with train and test scores
In [74]:
# defining a function to plot the confusion_matrix of a classification model built
def conf_mat(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("Actual Class")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted Class")

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Let's perform some parameters tuning on the three models above¶

Tuning Decision Tree Classifier¶

In [84]:
# Let's tune the decision tree classifier.
dtree_tuned = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini',class_weight={0:0.19,1:0.81},random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    "max_depth": np.arange(1, 14),
    "min_samples_leaf": [1, 2, 5, 7, 10, 15, 20],
    "max_leaf_nodes": [2, 3, 5, 10],
    "min_impurity_decrease": [0.001, 0.01, 0.1],
}

# Using f1_score as metrics used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(dtree_tuned, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
dtree_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
dtree_tuned.fit(x_train, y_train)

Conclusion¶

  • From the table above, it is clear that XGBoost Tuned model gave the best f1_score of 0.80 on the test set and good accuracy also of 0.93. We will therefore be going with this model.
  • As shown by our best model (XGBoost Tuned),Executive Designation, Passport, and Senior Manager Designation are the top three most important features determining whether a customer will purchase a travel package or not.

CUSTOMER PROFILE

  • Basic: Low income earners(customers earning average of 20,000 monthly), All Ages, Executive Designation
  • Deluxe: customers that generally earn monthly income between 20,001-24,999, not less than 22 years, Managers designation
  • Standard: customers that generally earn monthly income between 25,000-30,000, All Ages, Senior Managers Designation
  • Super Deluxe: Customers that generally earn between 30,001 and 34,999 monthly, not less than 28 years, and AVP designation
  • King: customers that generally earn 35,000 and above monthly income, not less than 26 years old, and VP designation

Summary of Insights and Recommendations¶

  • Most of the company customers that purchased travel package last year are less than 38 years. It is therefore recommended that the marketing campaign of the new product should be focused on customers within that age limit.

  • Over 66% of the travel packages sold last time were purchased by self enquiry customers. However, the company invited customers have higher likelihood of purchasing travel package than self enquiry customers. The marketing team is hereby advised that the two channels should be explored to the fullest in pitching the new products so as to make better sales.

  • Customers from Tiers 1 and 3 cities constitute 95% of the travel package purchasers at Visit-with-us. Most of the marketing efforts on the new product should therefore be concentrated in those two cities tiers.

  • Over 86% of those customers that purchase travel packages are salary earners and small business owners. It is therefore recommended that the new product should be marketed more to people with such occupations.

  • Most of the customers are males. The marketing team of the company should therefore take sales pitches with males more seriously.

  • Over 68% are either Single or Married. Marketing team should focus more of their sales pitches on customers with these marital statuses.

  • The customers with passport are far more likely to purchase travel packages than those without passport. The company should therefore focus thier sales pitches more on passport holding customers. The company may also begin to render passport processing facilitation services for their customers at a fee. This will serve as a complimentary service that will assist to drive sales of travel packages.

  • Customers who own cars are far more likely to purchase travel packages than those non-car owners. The marketing team should consider this in pitching their new product.

  • The bulk of the customers purchasing travel packages are either of Executive Status or Manager Status. These sets of customers are to be focused when pitching the new product.

  • Basic and Deluxe are the two products accounting for over 82% of the company sales last year. The new product to be introduced should be carefully designed to have both Basic and Deluxe variants so as to make good sales.

  • Customers who had at least 5 follow-ups from the company salespersons are more likely to purchase travel packages than other customers. This sales system should be adopted in the process of pitching the new product.

  • Most of those that purchase travel packages earn below 24,000 monthly. The company should therefore consider this when pitching the new product.
